ated short films]]<br />[[List of animated feature films|Theatrical animated feature films]]<br />[[List of animated television series|Television animated series]]\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| owner = [[Sony]]\n| num_employees = 255 (2018)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/sony-pictures-animation-pam-marsden-1202008817/ | title=Sony Pictures Animation Promotes Pam Marsden to Head of Production | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=March 14, 2017 | accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref>\n| parent = [[Sony Pictures|Sony Pictures Entertainment]]<br/>{{small|([[Sony Entertainment]])}}\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.sonypicturesanimation.com/|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Sony Pictures Animation Inc.''' is an American [[animation studio]] owned by [[Sony Pictures|Sony Pictures Entertainment]] through their [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group|Motion Picture Group]] division and founded on May 9, 2002. The studio's films are distributed worldwide by [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]] under their [[Columbia Pictures]] label, while all direct-to-video releases are released by [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]].\n\nThe first film produced by Sony Pictures Animation, ''[[Open Season (2006 film)|Open Season]]'', was released on September 29, 2006. Its latest release was ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]'' on August 13, 2019, with their next scheduled release set to be ''[[Connected (2020 film)|Connected]]'' on September 18, 2020.\n\n==History==\nIn 2001, [[Sony Pictures]] considered selling off its visual effects facility [[Sony Pictures Imageworks]]. After failing to find a suitable buyer, having been impressed with the [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] sequences of ''[[Stuart Little 2]]'' and seeing the box office successes of [[DreamWorks Animation]]'s ''[[Shrek]]'' and [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]/[[Pixar]]'s ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'', SPI was reconfigured to become an animation studio. ''[[Astro Boy (film)|Astro Boy]]'', which had been in development at Sony since 1997 as a live-action film, was set to be SPI's first all-CGI film, but never made it to fruition.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brodesser|first=Claude|title=Sony finds Rx for its f/x|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117856983|accessdate=September 1, 2011|newspaper=Variety|date=December 9, 2001}}</ref> On May 9, 2002, Sony Pictures Animation was established to develop characters, stories and movies with SPI taking over the digital production while maintaining its visual effects production.<ref>{{Cite press release | title = Sony Pictures Digital Entertainment Establishes Feature Animation Unit; Animation Executives Sandra Rabins and Penney Finkelman Cox Named to Top Posts | date = May 9, 2002 | url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sony-pictures-digital-entertainment-establishes-feature-animation-unit-animation-executives-sandra-rabins-and-penney-finkelman-cox-named-to-top-posts-77355402.html | accessdate = August 1, 2011}}</ref> Meanwhile, SPI produced two short films, the [[Academy Award]]-winning ''[[The ChubbChubbs!]]'' and ''[[Early Bloomer]]'', as a result of testing its strengths and weaknesses in producing all-CGI animation.<ref>{{cite web | last=Raugust | first=Karen | url=http://www.awn.com/articles/value-shorts/page/2%2C1 | title=The Value of Shorts | work=[[Animation World Network]] | date=May 30, 2006 | accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn its first anniversary on May 9, 2003, Sony Pictures Animation announced a full slate of animated projects in development: ''[[Open Season (2006 film)|Open Season]]'', an adaptation of a Celtic folk ballad ''[[Tam Lin]]'', ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'', ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'', and a feature-length film version of ''The ChubbChubbs!''.<ref>{{Cite press release | title = Sony Pictures Animation Announces Projects for Directors Jill Culton, Anthony Stacchi, Roger Allers, Brenda Chapman and the Brizzi Brothers Cox Named to Top Posts | date = May 9, 2003 | url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sony-pictures-animation-announces-projects-for-directors-jill-culton-anthony-stacchi-roger-allers-brenda-chapman-and-the-brizzi-brothers-55629432.html | accessdate = August 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIts first feature film was ''[[Open Season (2006 film)|Open Season]]'', released in September 2006, which became Sony's second-highest-grossing home entertainment film in 2007 and spawned three [[direct-to-video]] [[sequel]]s. Its second feature film, ''[[Surf's Up (film)|Surf's Up]]'' was released in June 2007, was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]], and won two Annie Awards. A [[Motion capture|motion-captured]] animated film titled ''Neanderthals''<ref>{{cite news | last=Adler | first=Shawn | url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/01/09/jon-favreau-gets-animated-for-neanderthals/ | title=Jon Favreau Gets Animated For 'Neanderthals' | publisher=MTV | date=January 9, 2008 | accessdate=August 1, 2011}}</ref> and written and produced by [[Jon Favreau]], was cancelled sometime in 2008<ref>{{cite web | last=Serrano | first=Armand | url=http://armandserrano.blogspot.com/2010/04/prehistoric.html |  title=Neanderthals | work=Armand Serrano Blog | date=April 19, 2010 | accessdate=August 1, 2011}}</ref> after four years in development. SPA's first 3D movie since the IMAX 3D release of ''[[Open Season (2006 film)|Open Season]]'', ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'', was released in September 2009 and was nominated for four Annie Awards, including Best Animated Feature. ''[[The Smurfs (film)|The Smurfs]]'' (2011) was the studio's first CGI/live-action hybrid. SPA's parent company [[Sony Pictures]] had partnered in 2007 with [[Aardman Animations]] to finance, co-produce and distribute feature films.<ref>{{cite news | author=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6518257.stm | title=Gromit animators sign Sony deal | publisher=BBC News | date=April 2, 2007 | accessdate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Together, they produced two films: ''[[Arthur Christmas]]'' (2011), and ''[[The Pirates! In an Adventure with Scientists!|The Pirates! Band of Misfits]]'' (2012), which was SPA's first stop-motion film. In September 2012, SPA released ''[[Hotel Transylvania]]'', which grossed over $350 million worldwide and launched a successful [[Hotel Transylvania (franchise)|franchise]] with two [[sequel]]s and a [[Hotel Transylvania: The Television Series|TV series]]. Two [[sequel]]s are released in 2013: ''[[The Smurfs 2]]'' and ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2]]''. SPA's latest releases are ''[[Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse]]'', an animated [[superhero film]] based on the [[Spider-Man]] comics and featuring the [[Miles Morales]] incarnation of the character, and ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]'', a sequel to the 2016 film ''[[The Angry Birds Movie]]'' produced by [[Rovio Animation]]. SPA has since signed [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] to a long-term deal with the studio to develop and direct original films.<ref>{{cite news|title=Genndy Tartakovsky Signs Overall Deal with Sony Pictures Animation|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=92429|accessdate=September 28, 2012|newspaper=ComingSoon.net|date=July 11, 2012|author=Sony Pictures Animation}}</ref>\n\nThe studio is currently working on ''[[Connected (2020 film)|Connected]]'', a robot apocalypse/road trip film written and directed by Michael Rianda and Jeff Rowe while produced by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]] (2020),<ref name=\"SPAVariety\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/kristine-belson-sony-pictures-animation-still-needs-a-big-hit-1202467942/|title= Annecy: Kristine Belson on Sony Pictures Animation's upcoming slate|date=June 15, 2017|work=Variety Magazine|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sonypicturesanimation.com/about.php?p=filmmakers&a=7|title=Sony Pictures Animation|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> ''Vivo'', and ''Hotel Transylvania 4'' (2021), and a sequel to ''Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse'' (2022). It has many other projects in development, including an animated ''[[Ghostbusters (franchise)#Animated film|Ghostbusters]]'' spin-off film,<ref name=\"The Wrap\">{{cite web|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title='Ghostbusters' Animated Movie in the Works at Sony Pictures Animation |url=http://www.thewrap.com/ghostbusters-animated-movie-in-the-works-at-sony-pictures-animation/|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=October 2, 2015 |date=October 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Ghostpost\">{{cite web|author1=Takao|title=Ghostbusters: Ecto Force postponed for new film|url=http://www.toonbarn.com/other-cartoons/ghostbusters-ecto-force-postponed-animated-feature/|website=ToonBarn|accessdate=September 2, 2017|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref> an untitled film from Jon Saunders,<ref name=AnimationDevelop>{{cite web |url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/animated-features-currently-in-development-152767.html|title=A List Of American Animated Features Currently In Development|work=Cartoon Brew|date=August 10, 2017|accessdate=August 21, 2017}}</ref> and two Genndy Tartakovsky projects: an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|R-rated]] comedy titled ''Fixed'' and ''Black Knight''.<ref name=\"DGTSA\">{{cite web|title='Hotel Transylvania' Helmer Genndy Tartakovsky Sets New Projects At Sony Pictures Animation|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|work=Deadline|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/hotel-transylvania-helmer-genndy-tartakovsky-fixed-black-knight-sony-pictures-animation-1202433175/\n|date=July 25, 2018|accessdate=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2014, the studio collaborated with [[Frederator Studios]]' [[Cartoon Hangover]] on ''[[GO! Cartoons]]'', an incubator series consisting of 12 short films, with at least one short film being developed into a series. The short films were funded by SPA, with the additional goal of attracting new talent for the studio.<ref>{{cite news|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|title=Sony Partners with Cartoon Hangover to Find New Talent|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/events/sony-partners-with-cartoon-hangover-to-find-new-talent/|accessdate=November 4, 2014 |publisher=Animation Magazine|date=November 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/top-stories/sony-animation-cartoon-hangover-launch-1st-incubator-film-the-summoning/|title=Sony Animation & Cartoon Hangover Launch 1st Incubator Film 'The Summoning'|work=Animation Magazine|date=November 7, 2017|last1=Milligan|first1=Mercedes|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Kristine Belson]], president of SPA, the studio produces films on a 1:1 development-to-production ratio, meaning that the studio puts films into development as much as it places films in production, unlike other animation studios.<ref name=\"SPAVariety\" />\n\nThe studio has plans to produce adult animated content for digital platforms.<ref name=\"SPAVariety\" />\n\n==Process==\nIn a similar fashion to the [[Warner Animation Group]] and [[Paramount Animation]], the studio outsources their films to other animation companies and visual effects studios, with the majority of their films being animated by [[Sony Pictures Imageworks]] (its sister company). Some films, such as ''[[Arthur Christmas]], [[The Pirates! Band of Misfits]],'' ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]'' and ''[[Wish Dragon]]'', were acquired by Sony Pictures Animation to be released under their banner while others, such as ''[[Goosebumps (film)|Goosebumps]]'' and ''[[Peter Rabbit (film)|Peter Rabbit]]'', were made with no involvement from the studio.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main article|List of Sony Pictures Animation productions}}\n\n==Franchises==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name || Years || Movies || First film release || Latest film release\n|-\n| ''[[Open Season (film series)|Open Se